164  enum ValueSelection {

169  enum DisplayLevel { NONE = 0, NORMAL = 1, VERBOSE = 2 };
170 
173  VariableSelection var_selection_schema;
174 
175  // This parameter describes which value to select for a given var.
176  ValueSelection value_selection_schema;
177 
178  // Maximum number of intervals that the initialization of impacts will scan
179  // per variable.
180  int initialization_splits;
181 
182  // The default phase will run heuristics periodically. This parameter
183  // indicates if we should run all heuristics, or a randomly selected
184  // one.
185  bool run_all_heuristics;
186 
187  // The distance in nodes between each run of the heuristics. A
188  // negative or null value will mean that we will not run heuristics
189  // at all.
190  int heuristic_period;
191 
192  // The failure limit for each heuristic that we run.
193  int heuristic_num_failures_limit;
194 
195  // Whether to keep the impact from the first search for other searches,
196  // or to recompute the impact for each new search.
197  bool persistent_impact;
198 
199  // Seed used to initialize the random part in some heuristics.
200  int random_seed;
201 
202  // This represents the amount of information displayed by the default search.
203  // NONE means no display, VERBOSE means extra information.
204  DisplayLevel display_level;
205 
206  // Should we use last conflict method. The default is false.
207  bool use_last_conflict;
208 
209  // When defined, this overrides the default impact based decision builder.
210  DecisionBuilder* decision_builder;
211 
212  DefaultPhaseParameters();
213 };

364  // This enum is used by Solver::MakePhase to specify how to select variables
365  // and values during the search.
366  // In Solver::MakePhase(const std::vector<IntVar*>&, IntVarStrategy,
367  // IntValueStrategy), variables are selected first, and then the associated
368  // value.
369  // In Solver::MakePhase(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, IndexEvaluator2,
370  // EvaluatorStrategy), the selection is done scanning every pair
371  // <variable, possible value>. The next selected pair is then the best among
372  // all possibilities, i.e. the pair with the smallest evaluation.
373  // As this is costly, two options are offered: static or dynamic evaluation.
374  enum EvaluatorStrategy {
375  // Pairs are compared at the first call of the selector, and results are
376  // cached. Next calls to the selector use the previous computation, and so
377  // are not up-to-date, e.g. some <variable, value> pairs may not be possible
378  // anymore due to propagation since the first to call.
379  CHOOSE_STATIC_GLOBAL_BEST,
380 
381  // Pairs are compared each time a variable is selected. That way all pairs
382  // are relevant and evaluation is accurate.
383  // This strategy runs in O(number-of-pairs) at each variable selection,
384  // versus O(1) in the static version.
385  CHOOSE_DYNAMIC_GLOBAL_BEST,
386  };
387 
388  // Used for scheduling. Not yet implemented.
389  enum SequenceStrategy {
390  SEQUENCE_DEFAULT,
391  SEQUENCE_SIMPLE,
392  CHOOSE_MIN_SLACK_RANK_FORWARD,
393  CHOOSE_RANDOM_RANK_FORWARD,
394  };

396  // This enum describes the straregy used to select the next interval variable
397  // and its value to be fixed.
398  enum IntervalStrategy {
399  // The default is INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD.
400  INTERVAL_DEFAULT,
401  // The simple is INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD.
402  INTERVAL_SIMPLE,
403  // Selects the variable with the lowest starting time of all variables,
404  // and fixes its starting time to this lowest value.
405  INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_FORWARD,
406  // Selects the variable with the highest ending time of all variables,
407  // and fixes the ending time to this highest values.
408  INTERVAL_SET_TIMES_BACKWARD
409  };

413  enum LocalSearchOperators {
425  TWOOPT,
426 
427  // Relocate: OROPT and RELOCATE.
428  // Operator which moves a sub-chain of a path to another position; the
429  // specified chain length is the fixed length of the chains being moved.
430  // When this length is 1, the operator simply moves a node to another
431  // position.
432  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5, for a chain
433  // length of 2 (where (1, 5) are first and last nodes of the path and can
434  // therefore not be moved):
435  // 1 -> 4 -> [2 -> 3] -> 5
436  // 1 -> [3 -> 4] -> 2 -> 5
437  //
438  // Using Relocate with chain lengths of 1, 2 and 3 together is equivalent
439  // to the OrOpt operator on a path. The OrOpt operator is a limited
440  // version of 3Opt (breaks 3 arcs on a path).
441  OROPT,
442 
443  // Relocate neighborhood with length of 1 (see OROPT comment).
444  RELOCATE,
445 
446  // Operator which exchanges the positions of two nodes.
447  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5
448  // (where (1, 5) are first and last nodes of the path and can therefore not
449  // be moved):
450  // 1 -> [3] -> [2] -> 4 -> 5
451  // 1 -> [4] -> 3 -> [2] -> 5
452  // 1 -> 2 -> [4] -> [3] -> 5
453  EXCHANGE,
454 
455  // Operator which cross exchanges the starting chains of 2 paths, including
456  // exchanging the whole paths.
457  // First and last nodes are not moved.
458  // Possible neighbors for the paths 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 and 6 -> 7 -> 8
459  // (where (1, 5) and (6, 8) are first and last nodes of the paths and can
460  // therefore not be moved):
461  // 1 -> [7] -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 6 -> [2] -> 8
462  // 1 -> [7] -> 4 -> 5 6 -> [2 -> 3] -> 8
463  // 1 -> [7] -> 5 6 -> [2 -> 3 -> 4] -> 8
464  CROSS,
465 
466  // Operator which inserts an inactive node into a path.
467  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
468  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
469  // 1 -> [5] -> 2 -> 3 -> 4
470  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4
471  // 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> [5] -> 4
472  MAKEACTIVE,
473 
474  // Operator which makes path nodes inactive.
475  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 (where 1 and 4 are
476  // first and last nodes of the path) are:
477  // 1 -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
478  // 1 -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
479  MAKEINACTIVE,
480 
481  // Operator which makes a "chain" of path nodes inactive.
482  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 (where 1 and 4 are
483  // first and last nodes of the path) are:
484  // 1 -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
485  // 1 -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
486  // 1 -> 4 with 2 and 3 inactive
487  MAKECHAININACTIVE,
488 
489  // Operator which replaces an active node by an inactive one.
490  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
491  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
492  // 1 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
493  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 4 with 3 inactive
494  SWAPACTIVE,
495 
496  // Operator which makes an inactive node active and an active one inactive.
497  // It is similar to SwapActiveOperator except that it tries to insert the
498  // inactive node in all possible positions instead of just the position of
499  // the node made inactive.
500  // Possible neighbors for the path 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 with 5 inactive
501  // (where 1 and 4 are first and last nodes of the path) are:
502  // 1 -> [5] -> 3 -> 4 with 2 inactive
503  // 1 -> 3 -> [5] -> 4 with 2 inactive
504  // 1 -> [5] -> 2 -> 4 with 3 inactive
505  // 1 -> 2 -> [5] -> 4 with 3 inactive
506  EXTENDEDSWAPACTIVE,
507 
508  // Operator which relaxes two sub-chains of three consecutive arcs each.
509  // Each sub-chain is defined by a start node and the next three arcs. Those
510  // six arcs are relaxed to build a new neighbor.
511  // PATHLNS explores all possible pairs of starting nodes and so defines
512  // n^2 neighbors, n being the number of nodes.
513  // Note that the two sub-chains can be part of the same path; they even may
514  // overlap.
515  PATHLNS,
516 
517  // Operator which relaxes one entire path and all inactive nodes, thus
518  // defining num_paths neighbors.
519  FULLPATHLNS,
520 
521  // Operator which relaxes all inactive nodes and one sub-chain of six
522  // consecutive arcs. That way the path can be improved by inserting
523  // inactive nodes or swapping arcs.
524  UNACTIVELNS,
525 
526  // Operator which defines one neighbor per variable. Each neighbor tries to
527  // increment by one the value of the corresponding variable. When a new
528  // solution is found the neighborhood is rebuilt from scratch, i.e., tries
529  // to increment values in the variable order.
530  // Consider for instance variables x and y. x is incremented one by one to
531  // its max, and when it is not possible to increment x anymore, y is
532  // incremented once. If this is a solution, then next neighbor tries to
533  // increment x.
534  INCREMENT,
535 
536  // Operator which defines a neighborhood to decrement values.
537  // The behavior is the same as INCREMENT, except values are decremented
538  // instead of incremented.
539  DECREMENT,
540 
541  // Operator which defines one neighbor per variable. Each neighbor relaxes
542  // one variable.
543  // When a new solution is found the neighborhood is rebuilt from scratch.
544  // Consider for instance variables x and y. First x is relaxed and the
545  // solver is looking for the best possible solution (with only x relaxed).
546  // Then y is relaxed, and the solver is looking for a new solution.
547  // If a new solution is found, then the next variable to be relaxed is x.
548  SIMPLELNS
549  };
550 
551  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeOperator associated with an evaluator
552  // to specify the neighborhood to create.
553  enum EvaluatorLocalSearchOperators {
554  // Lin–Kernighan local search.
555  // While the accumulated local gain is positive, perform a 2opt or a 3opt
556  // move followed by a series of 2opt moves. Return a neighbor for which the
557  // global gain is positive.
558  LK,
559 
560  // Sliding TSP operator.
561  // Uses an exact dynamic programming algorithm to solve the TSP
562  // corresponding to path sub-chains.
563  // For a subchain 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 -> 6, solves the TSP on
564  // nodes A, 2, 3, 4, 5, where A is a merger of nodes 1 and 6 such that
565  // cost(A,i) = cost(1,i) and cost(i,A) = cost(i,6).
566  TSPOPT,
567 
568  // TSP-base LNS.
569  // Randomly merge consecutive nodes until n "meta"-nodes remain and solve
570  // the corresponding TSP.
571  // This is an "unlimited" neighborhood which must be stopped by search
572  // limits. To force diversification, the operator iteratively forces each
573  // node to serve as base of a meta-node.
574  TSPLNS
575  };
576 
577  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeLocalSearchObjectiveFilter. It specifies
578  // the behavior of the objective filter to create. The goal is to define
579  // under which condition a move is accepted based on the current objective
580  // value.
581  enum LocalSearchFilterBound {
582  // Move is accepted when the current objective value >= objective.Min.
583  GE,
584  // Move is accepted when the current objective value <= objective.Max.
585  LE,
586  // Move is accepted when the current objective value is in the interval
587  // objective.Min .. objective.Max.
588  EQ
589  };

591  // This enum represents the three possible priorities for a demon in the
592  // Solver queue.
593  // Note: this is for advanced users only.
594  enum DemonPriority {
595  // DELAYED_PRIORITY is the lowest priority: Demons will be processed after
596  // VAR_PRIORITY and NORMAL_PRIORITY demons.
597  DELAYED_PRIORITY = 0,
598 
599  // VAR_PRIORITY is between DELAYED_PRIORITY and NORMAL_PRIORITY.
600  VAR_PRIORITY = 1,
601 
602  // NORMAL_PRIORITY is the highest priority: Demons will be processed first.
603  NORMAL_PRIORITY = 2,
604  };

606  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeIntervalVarRelation to specify the
607  // temporal relation between the two intervals t1 and t2.
608  enum BinaryIntervalRelation {
609  // t1 ends after t2 end, i.e. End(t1) >= End(t2) + delay.
610  ENDS_AFTER_END,
611 
612  // t1 ends after t2 start, i.e. End(t1) >= Start(t2) + delay.
613  ENDS_AFTER_START,
614 
615  // t1 ends at t2 end, i.e. End(t1) == End(t2) + delay.
616  ENDS_AT_END,
617 
618  // t1 ends at t2 start, i.e. End(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
619  ENDS_AT_START,
620 
621  // t1 starts after t2 end, i.e. Start(t1) >= End(t2) + delay.
622  STARTS_AFTER_END,
623 
624  // t1 starts after t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) >= Start(t2) + delay.
625  STARTS_AFTER_START,
626 
627  // t1 starts at t2 end, i.e. Start(t1) == End(t2) + delay.
628  STARTS_AT_END,
629 
630  // t1 starts at t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
631  STARTS_AT_START,
632 
633  // STARTS_AT_START and ENDS_AT_END at the same time.
634  // t1 starts at t2 start, i.e. Start(t1) == Start(t2) + delay.
635  // t1 ends at t2 end, i.e. End(t1) == End(t2).
636  STAYS_IN_SYNC
637  };
638 
639  // This enum is used in Solver::MakeIntervalVarRelation to specify the
640  // temporal relation between an interval t and an integer d.
641  enum UnaryIntervalRelation {
642  // t ends after d, i.e. End(t) >= d.
643  ENDS_AFTER,
644 
645  // t ends at d, i.e. End(t) == d.
646  ENDS_AT,
647 
648  // t ends before d, i.e. End(t) <= d.
649  ENDS_BEFORE,
650 
651  // t starts after d, i.e. Start(t) >= d.
652  STARTS_AFTER,
653 
654  // t starts at d, i.e. Start(t) == d.
655  STARTS_AT,
656 
657  // t starts before d, i.e. Start(t) <= d.
658  STARTS_BEFORE,
659 
660  // STARTS_BEFORE and ENDS_AFTER at the same time, i.e. d is in t.
661  // t starts before d, i.e. Start(t) <= d.
662  // t ends after d, i.e. End(t) >= d.
663  CROSS_DATE,
664 
665  // STARTS_AFTER or ENDS_BEFORE, i.e. d is not in t.
666  // t starts after d, i.e. Start(t) >= d.
667  // t ends before d, i.e. End(t) <= d.
668  AVOID_DATE
669  };

671  // The Solver is responsible for creating the search tree. Thanks to the
672  // DecisionBuilder, it creates a new decision with two branches at each node:
673  // left and right.
674  // The DecisionModification enum is used to specify how the branch selector
675  // should behave.
676  enum DecisionModification {
677  // Keeps the default behavior, i.e. apply left branch first, and then right
678  // branch in case of backtracking.
679  NO_CHANGE,
680 
681  // Right branches are ignored. This is used to make the code faster when
682  // backtrack makes no sense or is not useful.
683  // This is faster as there is no need to create one new node per decision.
684  KEEP_LEFT,
685 
686  // Left branches are ignored. This is used to make the code faster when
687  // backtrack makes no sense or is not useful.
688  // This is faster as there is no need to create one new node per decision.
689  KEEP_RIGHT,
690 
691  // Backtracks to the previous decisions, i.e. left and right branches are
692  // not applied.
693  KILL_BOTH,
694 
695  // Applies right branch first. Left branch will be applied in case of
696  // backtracking.
697  SWITCH_BRANCHES
698  };
699 
700  // This enum is used internally in private methods Solver::PushState and
701  // Solver::PopState to tag states in the search tree.
702  enum MarkerType { SENTINEL, SIMPLE_MARKER, CHOICE_POINT, REVERSIBLE_ACTION };
703 
704  // This enum represents the state of the solver w.r.t. the search.
705  enum SolverState {
706  OUTSIDE_SEARCH, // Before search, after search.
707  IN_ROOT_NODE, // Executing the root node.
708  IN_SEARCH, // Executing the search code.
709  AT_SOLUTION, // After successful NextSolution and before EndSearch.
710  NO_MORE_SOLUTIONS, // After failed NextSolution and before EndSearch.
711  PROBLEM_INFEASIBLE // After search, the model is infeasible.
712  };

749  // reversibility
750 
751  // SaveValue() saves the value of the corresponding object. It must be
752  // called before modifying the object. The value will be restored upon
753  // backtrack.
754  template <class T>
755  void SaveValue(T* o) {
756  InternalSaveValue(o);
757  }
758 
759  // Registers the given object as being reversible. By calling this method,
760  // the caller gives ownership of the object to the solver, which will
761  // delete it when there is a backtrack out of the current state.
762  //
763  // Returns the argument for convenience: this way, the caller may directly
764  // invoke a constructor in the argument, without having to store the pointer
765  // first.
766  //
767  // This function is only for users that define their own subclasses of
768  // BaseObject: for all subclasses predefined in the library, the
769  // corresponding factory methods (e.g., MakeIntVar(...),
770  // MakeAllDifferent(...) already take care of the registration.
771  template <typename T>
772  T* RevAlloc(T* object) {
773  return reinterpret_cast<T*>(SafeRevAlloc(object));
774  }
775 
776  // Like RevAlloc() above, but for an array of objects: the array
777  // must have been allocated with the new[] operator. The entire array
778  // will be deleted when backtracking out of the current state.
779  //
780  // This method is valid for arrays of int, int64, uint64, bool,
781  // BaseObject*, IntVar*, IntExpr*, and Constraint*.
782  template <typename T>
783  T* RevAllocArray(T* object) {
784  return reinterpret_cast<T*>(SafeRevAllocArray(object));
785  }
786 
787  // propagation
788 
789  // Adds the constraint 'c' to the model.
790  //
791  // After calling this method, and until there is a backtrack that undoes the
792  // addition, any assignment of variables to values must satisfy the given
793  // constraint in order to be considered feasible. There are two fairly
794  // different use cases:
795  //
796  // - the most common use case is modeling: the given constraint is really
797  // part of the problem that the user is trying to solve. In this use case,
798  // AddConstraint is called outside of search (i.e., with <tt>state() ==
799  // OUTSIDE_SEARCH</tt>). Most users should only use AddConstraint in this
800  // way. In this case, the constraint will belong to the model forever: it
801  // cannot not be removed by backtracking.
802  //
803  // - a rarer use case is that 'c' is not a real constraint of the model. It
804  // may be a constraint generated by a branching decision (a constraint whose
805  // goal is to restrict the search space), a symmetry breaking constraint (a
806  // constraint that does restrict the search space, but in a way that cannot
807  // have an impact on the quality of the solutions in the subtree), or an
808  // inferred constraint that, while having no semantic value to the model (it
809  // does not restrict the set of solutions), is worth having because we
810  // believe it may strengthen the propagation. In these cases, it happens
811  // that the constraint is added during the search (i.e., with state() ==
812  // IN_SEARCH or state() == IN_ROOT_NODE). When a constraint is
813  // added during a search, it applies only to the subtree of the search tree
814  // rooted at the current node, and will be automatically removed by
815  // backtracking.
816  //
817  // This method does not take ownership of the constraint. If the constraint
818  // has been created by any factory method (Solver::MakeXXX), it will
819  // automatically be deleted. However, power users who implement their own
820  // constraints should do: solver.AddConstraint(solver.RevAlloc(new
821  // MyConstraint(...));
822  void AddConstraint(Constraint* const c);
823  // Adds 'constraint' to the solver and marks it as a cast constraint, that
824  // is, a constraint created calling Var() on an expression. This is used
825  // internally.
826  void AddCastConstraint(CastConstraint* const constraint,
827  IntVar* const target_var, IntExpr* const expr);
828 
829  // @{
830  // Solves the problem using the given DecisionBuilder and returns true if a
831  // solution was found and accepted.
832  //
833  // These methods are the ones most users should use to search for a solution.
834  // Note that the definition of 'solution' is subtle. A solution here is
835  // defined as a leaf of the search tree with respect to the given decision
836  // builder for which there is no failure. What this means is that, contrary
837  // to intuition, a solution may not have all variables of the model bound.
838  // It is the responsibility of the decision builder to keep returning
839  // decisions until all variables are indeed bound. The most extreme
840  // counterexample is calling Solve with a trivial decision builder whose
841  // Next() method always returns nullptr. In this case, Solve immediately
842  // returns 'true', since not assigning any variable to any value is a
843  // solution, unless the root node propagation discovers that the model is
844  // infeasible.
845  //
846  // This function must be called either from outside of search,
847  // or from within the Next() method of a decision builder.
848  //
849  // Solve will terminate whenever any of the following event arise:
850  // * A search monitor asks the solver to terminate the search by calling
851  // solver()->FinishCurrentSearch().
852  // * A solution is found that is accepted by all search monitors, and none of
853  // the search monitors decides to search for another one.
854  //
855  // Upon search termination, there will be a series of backtracks all the way
856  // to the top level. This means that a user cannot expect to inspect the
857  // solution by querying variables after a call to Solve(): all the
858  // information will be lost. In order to do something with the solution, the
859  // user must either:
860  //
861  // * Use a search monitor that can process such a leaf. See, in particular,
862  // the SolutionCollector class.
863  // * Do not use Solve. Instead, use the more fine-grained approach using
864  // methods NewSearch(...), NextSolution(), and EndSearch().
865  //
866  // @param db The decision builder that will generate the search tree.
867  // @param monitors A vector of search monitors that will be notified of
868  // various events during the search. In their reaction to these events, such
869  // monitors may influence the search.
870  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db,
871  const std::vector<SearchMonitor*>& monitors);
872  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db);
873  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
874  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
875  SearchMonitor* const m2);
876  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
877  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3);
878  bool Solve(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
879  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3,
880  SearchMonitor* const m4);
881  // @}
882 
883  // @{
884  // Decomposed search.
885  // The code for a top level search should look like
886  // solver->NewSearch(db);
887  // while (solver->NextSolution()) {
888  // //.. use the current solution
889  // }
890  // solver()->EndSearch();
891 
892  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db,
893  const std::vector<SearchMonitor*>& monitors);
894  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db);
895  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
896  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
897  SearchMonitor* const m2);
898  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
899  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3);
900  void NewSearch(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
901  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3,
902  SearchMonitor* const m4);
903 
904  bool NextSolution();
905  void RestartSearch();
906  void EndSearch();
907  // @}
908 
909  // SolveAndCommit using a decision builder and up to three
910  // search monitors, usually one for the objective, one for the limits
911  // and one to collect solutions.
912  //
913  // The difference between a SolveAndCommit() and a Solve() method
914  // call is the fact that SolveAndCommit will not backtrack all
915  // modifications at the end of the search. This method is only
916  // usable during the Next() method of a decision builder.
917  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db,
918  const std::vector<SearchMonitor*>& monitors);
919  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db);
920  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1);
921  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
922  SearchMonitor* const m2);
923  bool SolveAndCommit(DecisionBuilder* const db, SearchMonitor* const m1,
924  SearchMonitor* const m2, SearchMonitor* const m3);
925

930  // failure. It will return false if the model is already inconsistent, or if
931  // adding the constraint makes it inconsistent.
932  bool CheckConstraint(Constraint* const ct);

1498  // Creates a constraint binding the arrays of variables "vars" and
1499  // "sorted_vars": sorted_vars[0] must be equal to the minimum of all
1500  // variables in vars, and so on: the value of sorted_vars[i] must be
1501  // equal to the i-th value of variables invars.
1502  //
1503  // This constraint propagates in both directions: from "vars" to
1504  // "sorted_vars" and vice-versa.
1505  //
1506  // Behind the scenes, this constraint maintains that:
1507  // - sorted is always increasing.
1508  // - whatever the values of vars, there exists a permutation that
1509  // injects its values into the sorted variables.
1510  //
1511  // For more info, please have a look at:
1512  // https://mpi-inf.mpg.de/~mehlhorn/ftp/Mehlhorn-Thiel.pdf
1513  Constraint* MakeSortingConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1514  const std::vector<IntVar*>& sorted);
1515  // TODO(user): Add void MakeSortedArray(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1516  // std::vector<IntVar*>* const
1517  // sorted);
1518

1520  // than right.

1522  const std::vector<IntVar*>& right);
1523 
1524  // Creates a constraint that enforces that left is lexicographically less
1525  // than or equal to right.
1526  Constraint* MakeLexicalLessOrEqual(const std::vector<IntVar*>& left,
1527  const std::vector<IntVar*>& right);
1528 
1529  // Creates a constraint that enforces that 'left' and 'right' both
1530  // represent permutations of [0..left.size()-1], and that 'right' is
1531  // the inverse permutation of 'left', i.e. for all i in
1532  // [0..left.size()-1], right[left[i]] = i.
1533  Constraint* MakeInversePermutationConstraint(
1534  const std::vector<IntVar*>& left, const std::vector<IntVar*>& right);

1565  // Prevent cycles. The "nexts" variables represent the next in the chain.
1566  // "active" variables indicate if the corresponding next variable is active;
1567  // this could be useful to model unperformed nodes in a routing problem.
1568  // A callback can be added to specify sink values (by default sink values
1569  // are values >= vars.size()). Ownership of the callback is passed to the
1570  // constraint.
1571  // If assume_paths is either not specified or true, the constraint assumes
1572  // the "nexts" variables represent paths (and performs a faster propagation);
1573  // otherwise the constraint assumes they represent a forest.
1574  Constraint* MakeNoCycle(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1575  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1576  IndexFilter1 sink_handler = nullptr);
1577  Constraint* MakeNoCycle(const std::vector<IntVar*>& nexts,
1578  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,
1579  IndexFilter1 sink_handler, bool assume_paths);

1585  // for those that do not loop upon themselves.

1588  // Creates a constraint which accumulates values along a path such that:
1589  // cumuls[next[i]] = cumuls[i] + transits[i].

1600  const std::vector<IntVar*>& active,

1602  const std::vector<IntVar*>& transits);

1634  // Contraint enforcing, for each pair (i,j) in precedences, i to be before j
1635  // in paths defined by next variables.
1636  // TODO(user): This constraint does not make holes in variable domains;
1637  // the implementation can easily be modified to do that; evaluate the impact
1638  // on models solved with local search.
1639  Constraint* MakePathPrecedenceConstraint(
1640  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts,
1641  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences);
1642  // Same as MakePathPrecedenceConstraint but ensures precedence pairs on some
1643  // paths follow a LIFO or FIFO order.
1644  // LIFO order: given 2 pairs (a,b) and (c,d), if a is before c on the path
1645  // then d must be before b or b must be before c.
1646  // FIFO order: given 2 pairs (a,b) and (c,d), if a is before c on the path
1647  // then b must be before d.
1648  // LIFO (resp. FIFO) orders are enforced only on paths starting by indices in
1649  // lifo_path_starts (resp. fifo_path_start).
1650  Constraint* MakePathPrecedenceConstraint(
1651  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts,
1652  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences,
1653  const std::vector<int>& lifo_path_starts,
1654  const std::vector<int>& fifo_path_starts);
1655  // Same as MakePathPrecedenceConstraint but will force i to be before j if
1656  // the sum of transits on the path from i to j is strictly positive.
1657  Constraint* MakePathTransitPrecedenceConstraint(
1658  std::vector<IntVar*> nexts, std::vector<IntVar*> transits,
1659  const std::vector<std::pair<int, int>>& precedences);
1660 #endif

1674  // This constraint create a finite automaton that will check the
1675  // sequence of variables vars. It uses a transition table called
1676  // 'transition_table'. Each transition is a triple
1677  // (current_state, variable_value, new_state).
1678  // The initial state is given, and the set of accepted states is decribed
1679  // by 'final_states'. These states are hidden inside the constraint.
1680  // Only the transitions (i.e. the variables) are visible.
1681  Constraint* MakeTransitionConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1682  const IntTupleSet& transition_table,
1683  int64 initial_state,
1684  const std::vector<int64>& final_states);
1685 
1686  // This constraint create a finite automaton that will check the

1688  // 'transition_table'. Each transition is a triple
1689  // (current_state, variable_value, new_state).
1690  // The initial state is given, and the set of accepted states is decribed
1691  // by 'final_states'. These states are hidden inside the constraint.
1692  // Only the transitions (i.e. the variables) are visible.
1693  Constraint* MakeTransitionConstraint(const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
1694  const IntTupleSet& transition_table,

1719  // This constraint states that all the boxes must not overlap.

1721  // (x_vars[i], y_vars[i]),

1723  // (x_vars[i] + x_size[i], y_vars[i]),

1726  // pushed like any box.

1880  // Creates and returns an interval variable that wraps around the given one,
1881  // relaxing the min start and end. Relaxing means making unbounded when
1882  // optional. If the variable is non-optional, this method returns
1883  // interval_var.
1884  //
1885  // More precisely, such an interval variable behaves as follows:
1886  // * When the underlying must be performed, the returned interval variable
1887  // behaves exactly as the underlying;
1888  // * When the underlying may or may not be performed, the returned interval
1889  // variable behaves like the underlying, except that it is unbounded on
1890  // the min side;
1891  // * When the underlying cannot be performed, the returned interval variable
1892  // is of duration 0 and must be performed in an interval unbounded on both
1893  // sides.
1894  //
1895  // This is very useful to implement propagators that may only modify
1896  // the start max or end max.
1897  IntervalVar* MakeIntervalRelaxedMin(IntervalVar* const interval_var);
1898 
1899  // Creates and returns an interval variable that wraps around the given one,
1900  // relaxing the max start and end. Relaxing means making unbounded when
1901  // optional. If the variable is non optional, this method returns
1902  // interval_var.
1903  //
1904  // More precisely, such an interval variable behaves as follows:
1905  // * When the underlying must be performed, the returned interval variable
1906  // behaves exactly as the underlying;
1907  // * When the underlying may or may not be performed, the returned interval
1908  // variable behaves like the underlying, except that it is unbounded on
1909  // the max side;
1910  // * When the underlying cannot be performed, the returned interval variable
1911  // is of duration 0 and must be performed in an interval unbounded on
1912  // both sides.
1913  //
1914  // This is very useful for implementing propagators that may only modify
1915  // the start min or end min.
1916  IntervalVar* MakeIntervalRelaxedMax(IntervalVar* const interval_var);

2143  // ----- Meta-heuristics -----
2144  // Search monitors which try to get the search out of local optima.
2145 
2146  // Creates a Tabu Search monitor.
2147  // In the context of local search the behavior is similar to MakeOptimize(),
2148  // creating an objective in a given sense. The behavior differs once a local
2149  // optimum is reached: thereafter solutions which degrade the value of the
2150  // objective are allowed if they are not "tabu". A solution is "tabu" if it
2151  // doesn't respect the following rules:
2152  // - improving the best solution found so far
2153  // - variables in the "keep" list must keep their value, variables in the
2154  // "forbid" list must not take the value they have in the list.
2155  // Variables with new values enter the tabu lists after each new solution
2156  // found and leave the lists after a given number of iterations (called
2157  // tenure). Only the variables passed to the method can enter the lists.
2158  // The tabu criterion is softened by the tabu factor which gives the number
2159  // of "tabu" violations which is tolerated; a factor of 1 means no violations
2160  // allowed; a factor of 0 means all violations are allowed.
2161 
2162  SearchMonitor* MakeTabuSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const v, int64 step,
2163  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
2164  int64 keep_tenure, int64 forbid_tenure,
2165  double tabu_factor);
2166 
2167  // Creates a Tabu Search based on the vars |vars|.
2168  // A solution is "tabu" if all the vars in |vars| keep their value.
2169  SearchMonitor* MakeGenericTabuSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const v,
2170  int64 step,
2171  const std::vector<IntVar*>& tabu_vars,
2172  int64 forbid_tenure);
2173 
2174  // Creates a Simulated Annealing monitor.
2175  // TODO(user): document behavior
2176  SearchMonitor* MakeSimulatedAnnealing(bool maximize, IntVar* const v,
2177  int64 step, int64 initial_temperature);
2178

2181  SearchMonitor* MakeGuidedLocalSearch(bool maximize, IntVar* const objective,
2182  IndexEvaluator2 objective_function,
2183  int64 step,
2184  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars,
2185  double penalty_factor);

2188  IndexEvaluator3 objective_function, int64 step,

2190  const std::vector<IntVar*>& secondary_vars, double penalty_factor);

2348  // Creates a decision builder which sequentially composes decision builders.
2349  // At each leaf of a decision builder, the next decision builder is therefore
2350  // called. For instance, Compose(db1, db2) will result in the following tree:
2351  // d1 tree |
2352  // / | \ |
2353  // db1 leaves |
2354  // / | \ |
2355  // db2 tree db2 tree db2 tree |
2356  DecisionBuilder* Compose(DecisionBuilder* const db1,
2357  DecisionBuilder* const db2);
2358  DecisionBuilder* Compose(DecisionBuilder* const db1,
2359  DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2360  DecisionBuilder* const db3);
2361  DecisionBuilder* Compose(DecisionBuilder* const db1,
2362  DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2363  DecisionBuilder* const db3,
2364  DecisionBuilder* const db4);
2365  DecisionBuilder* Compose(const std::vector<DecisionBuilder*>& dbs);
2366 
2367  // Creates a decision builder which will create a search tree where each
2368  // decision builder is called from the top of the search tree. For instance
2369  // the decision builder Try(db1, db2) will entirely explore the search tree
2370  // of db1 then the one of db2, resulting in the following search tree:
2371  // Tree root |
2372  // / \ |
2373  // db1 tree db2 tree |
2374  //
2375  // This is very handy to try a decision builder which partially explores the
2376  // search space and if it fails to try another decision builder.
2377  //
2378  // TODO(user): The search tree can be balanced by using binary
2379  // "Try"-builders "recursively". For instance, Try(a,b,c,d) will give a tree
2380  // unbalanced to the right, whereas Try(Try(a,b), Try(b,c)) will give a
2381  // balanced tree. Investigate if we should only provide the binary version
2382  // and/or if we should balance automatically.
2383  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2);
2384  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2385  DecisionBuilder* const db3);
2386  DecisionBuilder* Try(DecisionBuilder* const db1, DecisionBuilder* const db2,
2387  DecisionBuilder* const db3, DecisionBuilder* const db4);
2388  DecisionBuilder* Try(const std::vector<DecisionBuilder*>& dbs);

2582  // Creates a large neighborhood search operator which creates fragments (set
2583  // of relaxed variables) with up to number_of_variables random variables
2584  // (sampling with replacement is performed meaning that at most
2585  // number_of_variables variables are selected). Warning: this operator will
2586  // always return neighbors; using it without a search limit will result in a
2587  // non-ending search.
2588  // Optionally a random seed can be specified.

2595  // Creates a local search operator that tries to move the assignment of some
2596  // variables toward a target. The target is given as an Assignment. This
2597  // operator generates neighbors in which the only difference compared to the
2598  // current state is that one variable that belongs to the target assignment
2599  // is set to its target value.
2600  LocalSearchOperator* MakeMoveTowardTargetOperator(const Assignment& target);
2601 
2602  // Creates a local search operator that tries to move the assignment of some
2603  // variables toward a target. The target is given either as two vectors: a
2604  // vector of variables and a vector of associated target values. The two
2605  // vectors should be of the same length. This operator generates neighbors in
2606  // which the only difference compared to the current state is that one
2607  // variable that belongs to the given vector is set to its target value.
2608  LocalSearchOperator* MakeMoveTowardTargetOperator(
2609  const std::vector<IntVar*>& variables,
2610  const std::vector<int64>& target_values);
2611 
2612  // Creates a local search operator which concatenates a vector of operators.
2613  // Each operator from the vector is called sequentially. By default, when a
2614  // neighbor is found the neighborhood exploration restarts from the last
2615  // active operator (the one which produced the neighbor).
2616  // This can be overridden by setting restart to true to force the exploration
2617  // to start from the first operator in the vector.
2618  // The default behavior can also be overridden using an evaluation callback to
2619  // set the order in which the operators are explored (the callback is called
2620  // in LocalSearchOperator::Start()). The first argument of the callback is
2621  // the index of the operator which produced the last move, the second
2622  // argument is the index of the operator to be evaluated.
2623  // Ownership of the callback is taken by ConcatenateOperators.
2624  //
2625  // Example:
2626  //
2627  // const int kPriorities = {10, 100, 10, 0};
2628  // int64 Evaluate(int active_operator, int current_operator) {
2629  // return kPriorities[current_operator];
2630  // }
2631  //
2632  // LocalSearchOperator* concat =
2633  // solver.ConcatenateOperators(operators,
2634  // NewPermanentCallback(&Evaluate));
2635  //
2636  // The elements of the vector operators will be sorted by increasing priority
2637  // and explored in that order (tie-breaks are handled by keeping the relative
2638  // operator order in the vector). This would result in the following order:
2639  // operators[3], operators[0], operators[2], operators[1].
2640  //
2641  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2642  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops);
2643  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2644  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops, bool restart);
2645  LocalSearchOperator* ConcatenateOperators(
2646  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops,
2647  std::function<int64(int, int)> evaluator);
2648  // Randomized version of local search concatenator; calls a random operator
2649  // at each call to MakeNextNeighbor().
2650  LocalSearchOperator* RandomConcatenateOperators(
2651  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops);
2652 
2653  // Randomized version of local search concatenator; calls a random operator
2654  // at each call to MakeNextNeighbor(). The provided seed is used to
2655  // initialize the random number generator.
2656  LocalSearchOperator* RandomConcatenateOperators(
2657  const std::vector<LocalSearchOperator*>& ops, int32 seed);
2658 
2659  // Creates a local search operator that wraps another local search
2660  // operator and limits the number of neighbors explored (i.e., calls
2661  // to MakeNextNeighbor from the current solution (between two calls
2662  // to Start()). When this limit is reached, MakeNextNeighbor()
2663  // returns false. The counter is cleared when Start() is called.
2664  LocalSearchOperator* MakeNeighborhoodLimit(LocalSearchOperator* const op,
2665  int64 limit);
2666 
2667  // Local Search decision builders factories.
2668  // Local search is used to improve a given solution. This initial solution
2669  // can be specified either by an Assignment or by a DecisionBulder, and the
2670  // corresponding variables, the initial solution being the first solution
2671  // found by the DecisionBuilder.
2672  // The LocalSearchPhaseParameters parameter holds the actual definition of
2673  // the local search phase:
2674  // - a local search operator used to explore the neighborhood of the current
2675  // solution,
2676  // - a decision builder to instantiate unbound variables once a neighbor has
2677  // been defined; in the case of LNS-based operators instantiates fragment
2678  // variables; search monitors can be added to this sub-search by wrapping
2679  // the decision builder with MakeSolveOnce.
2680  // - a search limit specifying how long local search looks for neighbors
2681  // before accepting one; the last neighbor is always taken and in the case
2682  // of a greedy search, this corresponds to the best local neighbor;
2683  // first-accept (which is the default behavior) can be modeled using a
2684  // solution found limit of 1,
2685  // - a vector of local search filters used to speed up the search by pruning
2686  // unfeasible neighbors.
2687  // Metaheuristics can be added by defining specialized search monitors;
2688  // currently down/up-hill climbing is available through OptimizeVar, as well
2689  // as Guided Local Search, Tabu Search and Simulated Annealing.
2690  //
2691  // TODO(user): Make a variant which runs a local search after each
2692  // solution found in a DFS.
2693 
2694  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2695  Assignment* const assignment,
2696  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2697  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2698  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2699  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2700  // Variant with a sub_decison_builder specific to the first solution.
2701  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2702  const std::vector<IntVar*>& vars, DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2703  DecisionBuilder* const first_solution_sub_decision_builder,
2704  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);
2705  DecisionBuilder* MakeLocalSearchPhase(
2706  const std::vector<SequenceVar*>& vars,
2707  DecisionBuilder* const first_solution,
2708  LocalSearchPhaseParameters* const parameters);

2788  // All-in-one SaveAndSetValue.
2789  template <class T>
2790  void SaveAndSetValue(T* adr, T val) {

2794  }
2795  }

2801  InternalSaveValue(adr);
2802  (*adr) += val;
2803  }
2804  }

3020  // Returns the Search object that is at the bottom of the search stack.
3021  // Contrast with ActiveSearch(), which returns the search at the
3022  // top of the stack.
3023  Search* TopLevelSearch() const { return searches_.at(1); }
3024  // Returns the Search object which is the parent of the active search, i.e.,
3025  // the search below the top of the stack. If the active search is at the
3026  // bottom of the stack, returns the active search.
3027  Search* ParentSearch() const {
3028  const size_t search_size = searches_.size();
3029  DCHECK_GT(search_size, 1);
3030  return searches_[search_size - 2];
3031  }

3123 // A BaseObject is the root of all reversibly allocated objects.
3124 // A DebugString method and the associated << operator are implemented
3125 // as a convenience.
3126 
3127 class BaseObject {
3128  public:
3129  BaseObject() {}
3130  virtual ~BaseObject() {}
3131  virtual std::string DebugString() const { return "BaseObject"; }
3132 
3133  private:
3134  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(BaseObject);
3135 };
3136 
3137 std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& out, const BaseObject* o); // NOLINT
3138 
3139 // The PropagationBaseObject is a subclass of BaseObject that is also
3140 // friend to the Solver class. It allows accessing methods useful when
3141 // writing new constraints or new expressions.
3142 class PropagationBaseObject : public BaseObject {
3143  public:
3144  explicit PropagationBaseObject(Solver* const s) : solver_(s) {}
3145  ~PropagationBaseObject() override {}
3146 
3147  std::string DebugString() const override {
3148  if (name().empty()) {
3149  return "PropagationBaseObject";
3150  } else {
3151  return absl::StrFormat("PropagationBaseObject: %s", name());
3152  }
3153  }
3154  Solver* solver() const { return solver_; }
3155  // This method freezes the propagation queue. It is useful when you
3156  // need to apply multiple modifications at once.
3157  void FreezeQueue() { solver_->FreezeQueue(); }
3158 
3159  // This method unfreezes the propagation queue. All modifications
3160  // that happened when the queue was frozen will be processed.
3161  void UnfreezeQueue() { solver_->UnfreezeQueue(); }
3162 
3163  // This method pushes the demon onto the propagation queue. It will
3164  // be processed directly if the queue is empty. It will be enqueued
3165  // according to its priority otherwise.
3166  void EnqueueDelayedDemon(Demon* const d) { solver_->EnqueueDelayedDemon(d); }
3167  void EnqueueVar(Demon* const d) { solver_->EnqueueVar(d); }
3168  void ExecuteAll(const SimpleRevFIFO<Demon*>& demons);
3169  void EnqueueAll(const SimpleRevFIFO<Demon*>& demons);
3170 
3171 #if !defined(SWIG)
3172  // This method sets a callback that will be called if a failure
3173  // happens during the propagation of the queue.
3174  void set_action_on_fail(Solver::Action a) {
3175  solver_->set_action_on_fail(std::move(a));
3176  }
3177 #endif // !defined(SWIG)
3178 
3179  // This method clears the failure callback.
3180  void reset_action_on_fail() { solver_->reset_action_on_fail(); }
3181 
3182  // Shortcut for variable cleaner.
3183  void set_variable_to_clean_on_fail(IntVar* v) {
3184  solver_->set_variable_to_clean_on_fail(v);
3185  }
3186 
3187  // Object naming.
3188  virtual std::string name() const;
3189  void set_name(const std::string& name);
3190  // Returns whether the object has been named or not.
3191  bool HasName() const;
3192  // Returns a base name for automatic naming.
3193  virtual std::string BaseName() const;
3194 
3195  private:
3196  Solver* const solver_;
3197  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(PropagationBaseObject);
3198 };

3200 // A Decision represents a choice point in the search tree. The two main
3201 // methods are Apply() to go left, or Refute() to go right.
3202 class Decision : public BaseObject {
3203  public:
3204  Decision() {}
3205  ~Decision() override {}
3206 
3207  // Apply will be called first when the decision is executed.
3208  virtual void Apply(Solver* const s) = 0;
3209 
3210  // Refute will be called after a backtrack.
3211  virtual void Refute(Solver* const s) = 0;
3212 
3213  std::string DebugString() const override { return "Decision"; }
3214  // Accepts the given visitor.
3215  virtual void Accept(DecisionVisitor* const visitor) const;
3216 
3217  private:
3218  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Decision);
3219 };
3220 
3221 // A DecisionVisitor is used to inspect a decision.
3222 // It contains virtual methods for all type of 'declared' decisions.
3223 class DecisionVisitor : public BaseObject {
3224  public:
3225  DecisionVisitor() {}
3226  ~DecisionVisitor() override {}
3227  virtual void VisitSetVariableValue(IntVar* const var, int64 value);
3228  virtual void VisitSplitVariableDomain(IntVar* const var, int64 value,
3229  bool start_with_lower_half);
3230  virtual void VisitScheduleOrPostpone(IntervalVar* const var, int64 est);
3231  virtual void VisitScheduleOrExpedite(IntervalVar* const var, int64 est);
3232  virtual void VisitRankFirstInterval(SequenceVar* const sequence, int index);
3233  virtual void VisitRankLastInterval(SequenceVar* const sequence, int index);
3234  virtual void VisitUnknownDecision();
3235 
3236  private:
3237  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(DecisionVisitor);
3238 };
3239 
3240 // A DecisionBuilder is responsible for creating the search tree. The
3241 // important method is Next(), which returns the next decision to execute.
3242 class DecisionBuilder : public BaseObject {
3243  public:
3244  DecisionBuilder() {}
3245  ~DecisionBuilder() override {}
3246  // This is the main method of the decision builder class. It must
3247  // return a decision (an instance of the class Decision). If it
3248  // returns nullptr, this means that the decision builder has finished
3249  // its work.
3250  virtual Decision* Next(Solver* const s) = 0;
3251  std::string DebugString() const override;
3252 #if !defined(SWIG)
3253  // This method will be called at the start of the search. It asks
3254  // the decision builder if it wants to append search monitors to the
3255  // list of active monitors for this search. Please note there are no
3256  // checks at this point for duplication.
3257  virtual void AppendMonitors(Solver* const solver,
3258  std::vector<SearchMonitor*>* const extras);
3259  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3260 #endif
3261 
3262  private:
3263  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(DecisionBuilder);
3264 };
3265 
3266 // A Demon is the base element of a propagation queue. It is the main
3267 // object responsible for implementing the actual propagation
3268 // of the constraint and pruning the inconsistent values in the domains
3269 // of the variables. The main concept is that demons are listeners that are
3270 // attached to the variables and listen to their modifications.
3271 // There are two methods:
3272 // - Run() is the actual method called when the demon is processed.
3273 // - priority() returns its priority. Standard priorities are slow, normal
3274 // or fast. "immediate" is reserved for variables and is treated separately.
3275 class Demon : public BaseObject {
3276  public:
3277  // This indicates the priority of a demon. Immediate demons are treated
3278  // separately and corresponds to variables.
3279  Demon() : stamp_(GG_ULONGLONG(0)) {}
3280  ~Demon() override {}
3281 
3282  // This is the main callback of the demon.
3283  virtual void Run(Solver* const s) = 0;
3284 
3285  // This method returns the priority of the demon. Usually a demon is
3286  // fast, slow or normal. Immediate demons are reserved for internal
3287  // use to maintain variables.
3288  virtual Solver::DemonPriority priority() const;
3289 
3290  std::string DebugString() const override;
3291 
3292  // This method inhibits the demon in the search tree below the
3293  // current position.
3294  void inhibit(Solver* const s);
3295 
3296  // This method un-inhibits the demon that was previously inhibited.
3297  void desinhibit(Solver* const s);
3298 
3299  private:
3300  friend class Queue;
3301  void set_stamp(int64 stamp) { stamp_ = stamp; }
3302  uint64 stamp() const { return stamp_; }
3303  uint64 stamp_;
3304  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Demon);
3305 };

3551 
3552 // A constraint is the main modeling object. It provides two methods:
3553 // - Post() is responsible for creating the demons and attaching them to
3554 // immediate demons().
3555 // - InitialPropagate() is called once just after Post and performs
3556 // the initial propagation. The subsequent propagations will be performed
3557 // by the demons Posted during the post() method.
3558 class Constraint : public PropagationBaseObject {
3559  public:
3560  explicit Constraint(Solver* const solver) : PropagationBaseObject(solver) {}
3561  ~Constraint() override {}
3562 
3563  // This method is called when the constraint is processed by the
3564  // solver. Its main usage is to attach demons to variables.
3565  virtual void Post() = 0;
3566 
3567  // This method performs the initial propagation of the
3568  // constraint. It is called just after the post.
3569  virtual void InitialPropagate() = 0;
3570  std::string DebugString() const override;
3571 
3572  // Calls Post and then Propagate to initialize the constraints. This
3573  // is usually done in the root node.
3574  void PostAndPropagate();
3575 
3576  // Accepts the given visitor.
3577  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3578 
3579  // Is the constraint created by a cast from expression to integer variable?
3580  bool IsCastConstraint() const;
3581 
3582  // Creates a Boolean variable representing the status of the constraint (false
3583  // = constraint is violated, true = constraint is satisfied). It returns
3584  // nullptr if the constraint does not support this API.
3585  virtual IntVar* Var();
3586 
3587  private:
3588  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(Constraint);
3589 };
3590 
3591 // Cast constraints are special channeling constraints designed
3592 // to keep a variable in sync with an expression. They are
3593 // created internally when Var() is called on a subclass of IntExpr.
3594 class CastConstraint : public Constraint {
3595  public:
3596  CastConstraint(Solver* const solver, IntVar* const target_var)
3597  : Constraint(solver), target_var_(target_var) {
3598  CHECK(target_var != nullptr);
3599  }
3600  ~CastConstraint() override {}
3601 
3602  IntVar* target_var() const { return target_var_; }
3603 
3604  protected:
3605  IntVar* const target_var_;
3606 };

3608 // A search monitor is a simple set of callbacks to monitor all search events
3609 class SearchMonitor : public BaseObject {
3610  public:
3611  static const int kNoProgress = -1;
3612 
3613  explicit SearchMonitor(Solver* const s) : solver_(s) {}
3614  ~SearchMonitor() override {}
3615  // Beginning of the search.
3616  virtual void EnterSearch();
3617 
3618  // Restart the search.
3619  virtual void RestartSearch();
3620 
3621  // End of the search.
3622  virtual void ExitSearch();
3623 
3624  // Before calling DecisionBuilder::Next.
3625  virtual void BeginNextDecision(DecisionBuilder* const b);
3626 
3627  // After calling DecisionBuilder::Next, along with the returned decision.
3628  virtual void EndNextDecision(DecisionBuilder* const b, Decision* const d);
3629 
3630  // Before applying the decision.
3631  virtual void ApplyDecision(Decision* const d);
3632 
3633  // Before refuting the decision.
3634  virtual void RefuteDecision(Decision* const d);
3635 
3636  // Just after refuting or applying the decision, apply is true after Apply.
3637  // This is called only if the Apply() or Refute() methods have not failed.
3638  virtual void AfterDecision(Decision* const d, bool apply);
3639 
3640  // Just when the failure occurs.
3641  virtual void BeginFail();
3642 
3643  // After completing the backtrack.
3644  virtual void EndFail();
3645 
3646  // Before the initial propagation.
3647  virtual void BeginInitialPropagation();
3648 
3649  // After the initial propagation.
3650  virtual void EndInitialPropagation();
3651 
3652  // This method is called when a solution is found. It asserts whether the
3653  // solution is valid. A value of false indicates that the solution
3654  // should be discarded.
3655  virtual bool AcceptSolution();
3656 
3657  // This method is called when a valid solution is found. If the
3658  // return value is true, then search will resume after. If the result
3659  // is false, then search will stop there.
3660  virtual bool AtSolution();
3661 
3662  // When the search tree is finished.
3663  virtual void NoMoreSolutions();
3664 
3665  // When a local optimum is reached. If 'true' is returned, the last solution
3666  // is discarded and the search proceeds with the next one.
3667  virtual bool LocalOptimum();
3668 
3669  //
3670  virtual bool AcceptDelta(Assignment* delta, Assignment* deltadelta);
3671 
3672  // After accepting a neighbor during local search.
3673  virtual void AcceptNeighbor();
3674 
3675  // After accepting an unchecked neighbor during local search.
3676  virtual void AcceptUncheckedNeighbor();
3677 
3678  // Returns true if the limit of solutions has been reached including
3679  // unchecked solutions.
3680  virtual bool IsUncheckedSolutionLimitReached() { return false; }
3681 
3682  Solver* solver() const { return solver_; }
3683 
3684  // Periodic call to check limits in long running methods.
3685  virtual void PeriodicCheck();
3686 
3687  // Returns a percentage representing the propress of the search before
3688  // reaching limits.
3689  virtual int ProgressPercent() { return kNoProgress; }
3690 
3691  // Accepts the given model visitor.
3692  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3693 
3694  // Registers itself on the solver such that it gets notified of the search
3695  // and propagation events.
3696  virtual void Install();
3697 
3698  private:
3699  Solver* const solver_;
3700  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(SearchMonitor);
3701 };
3702 
3703 // This class adds reversibility to a POD type.
3704 // It contains the stamp optimization. i.e. the SaveValue call is done
3705 // only once per node of the search tree. Please note that actual
3706 // stamps always starts at 1, thus an initial value of 0 will always
3707 // trigger the first SaveValue.
3708 template <class T>
3709 class Rev {
3710  public:
3711  explicit Rev(const T& val) : stamp_(0), value_(val) {}
3712 
3713  const T& Value() const { return value_; }
3714 
3715  void SetValue(Solver* const s, const T& val) {
3716  if (val != value_) {
3717  if (stamp_ < s->stamp()) {
3718  s->SaveValue(&value_);
3719  stamp_ = s->stamp();
3720  }
3721  value_ = val;
3722  }
3723  }
3724 
3725  private:
3726  uint64 stamp_;
3727  T value_;
3728 };
3729 
3730 // Subclass of Rev<T> which adds numerical operations.
3731 template <class T>
3732 class NumericalRev : public Rev<T> {
3733  public:
3734  explicit NumericalRev(const T& val) : Rev<T>(val) {}
3735 
3736  void Add(Solver* const s, const T& to_add) {
3737  this->SetValue(s, this->Value() + to_add);
3738  }
3739 
3740  void Incr(Solver* const s) { Add(s, 1); }
3741 
3742  void Decr(Solver* const s) { Add(s, -1); }
3743 };
3744 
3745 // Reversible array of POD types.
3746 // It contains the stamp optimization. I.e., the SaveValue call is done only
3747 // once per node of the search tree.
3748 // Please note that actual stamp always starts at 1, thus an initial value of
3749 // 0 always triggers the first SaveValue.
3750 template <class T>
3751 class RevArray {
3752  public:
3753  RevArray(int size, const T& val)
3754  : stamps_(new uint64[size]), values_(new T[size]), size_(size) {
3755  for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
3756  stamps_[i] = 0;
3757  values_[i] = val;
3758  }
3759  }
3760 
3761  ~RevArray() {}
3762 
3763  int64 size() const { return size_; }
3764 
3765  const T& Value(int index) const { return values_[index]; }
3766 
3767 #if !defined(SWIG)
3768  const T& operator[](int index) const { return values_[index]; }
3769 #endif
3770 
3771  void SetValue(Solver* const s, int index, const T& val) {
3772  DCHECK_LT(index, size_);
3773  if (val != values_[index]) {
3774  if (stamps_[index] < s->stamp()) {
3775  s->SaveValue(&values_[index]);
3776  stamps_[index] = s->stamp();
3777  }
3778  values_[index] = val;
3779  }
3780  }
3781 
3782  private:
3783  std::unique_ptr<uint64[]> stamps_;
3784  std::unique_ptr<T[]> values_;
3785  const int size_;
3786 };
3787 
3788 // Subclass of RevArray<T> which adds numerical operations.
3789 template <class T>
3790 class NumericalRevArray : public RevArray<T> {
3791  public:
3792  NumericalRevArray(int size, const T& val) : RevArray<T>(size, val) {}
3793 
3794  void Add(Solver* const s, int index, const T& to_add) {
3795  this->SetValue(s, index, this->Value(index) + to_add);
3796  }
3797 
3798  void Incr(Solver* const s, int index) { Add(s, index, 1); }
3799 
3800  void Decr(Solver* const s, int index) { Add(s, index, -1); }
3801 };

3803 // The class IntExpr is the base of all integer expressions in
3804 // constraint programming.
3805 // It contains the basic protocol for an expression:
3806 // - setting and modifying its bound
3807 // - querying if it is bound
3808 // - listening to events modifying its bounds
3809 // - casting it into a variable (instance of IntVar)
3810 class IntExpr : public PropagationBaseObject {
3811  public:
3812  explicit IntExpr(Solver* const s) : PropagationBaseObject(s) {}
3813  ~IntExpr() override {}
3814 
3815  virtual int64 Min() const = 0;
3816  virtual void SetMin(int64 m) = 0;
3817  virtual int64 Max() const = 0;
3818  virtual void SetMax(int64 m) = 0;
3819 
3820  // By default calls Min() and Max(), but can be redefined when Min and Max
3821  // code can be factorized.
3822  virtual void Range(int64* l, int64* u) {
3823  *l = Min();
3824  *u = Max();
3825  }
3826  // This method sets both the min and the max of the expression.
3827  virtual void SetRange(int64 l, int64 u) {
3828  SetMin(l);
3829  SetMax(u);
3830  }
3831 
3832  // This method sets the value of the expression.
3833  virtual void SetValue(int64 v) { SetRange(v, v); }
3834 
3835  // Returns true if the min and the max of the expression are equal.
3836  virtual bool Bound() const { return (Min() == Max()); }
3837 
3838  // Returns true if the expression is indeed a variable.
3839  virtual bool IsVar() const { return false; }
3840 
3841  // Creates a variable from the expression.
3842  virtual IntVar* Var() = 0;
3843 
3844  // Creates a variable from the expression and set the name of the
3845  // resulting var. If the expression is already a variable, then it
3846  // will set the name of the expression, possibly overwriting it.
3847  // This is just a shortcut to Var() followed by set_name().
3848  IntVar* VarWithName(const std::string& name);
3849 
3850  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3851  virtual void WhenRange(Demon* d) = 0;
3852  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3853  void WhenRange(Solver::Closure closure) {
3854  WhenRange(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
3855  }
3856 
3857 #if !defined(SWIG)
3858  // Attach a demon that will watch the min or the max of the expression.
3859  void WhenRange(Solver::Action action) {
3860  WhenRange(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
3861  }
3862 #endif // SWIG
3863 
3864  // Accepts the given visitor.
3865  virtual void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const;
3866 
3867  private:
3868  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(IntExpr);
3869 };

3871 // The class Iterator has two direct subclasses. HoleIterators
3872 // iterates over all holes, that is value removed between the
3873 // current min and max of the variable since the last time the
3874 // variable was processed in the queue. DomainIterators iterates
3875 // over all elements of the variable domain. Both iterators are not
3876 // robust to domain changes. Hole iterators can also report values outside
3877 // the current min and max of the variable.
3878 
3879 // HoleIterators should only be called from a demon attached to the
3880 // variable that has created this iterator.
3881 
3882 // IntVar* current_var;
3883 // std::unique_ptr<IntVarIterator> it(current_var->MakeHoleIterator(false));
3884 // for (const int64 hole : InitAndGetValues(it)) {
3885 // // use the hole
3886 // }
3887 
3888 class IntVarIterator : public BaseObject {
3889  public:
3890  ~IntVarIterator() override {}
3891 
3892  // This method must be called before each loop.
3893  virtual void Init() = 0;
3894 
3895  // This method indicates if we can call Value() or not.
3896  virtual bool Ok() const = 0;
3897 
3898  // This method returns the current value of the iterator.
3899  virtual int64 Value() const = 0;
3900 
3901  // This method moves the iterator to the next value.
3902  virtual void Next() = 0;
3903 
3904  // Pretty Print.
3905  std::string DebugString() const override { return "IntVar::Iterator"; }
3906 };

3908 #ifndef SWIG
3909 // Utility class to encapsulate an IntVarIterator and use it in a range-based
3910 // loop. See the code snippet above IntVarIterator.
3911 //
3912 // It contains DEBUG_MODE-enabled code that DCHECKs that the
3913 // same iterator instance isn't being iterated on in multiple places
3914 // simultaneously.
3915 class InitAndGetValues {
3916  public:
3917  explicit InitAndGetValues(IntVarIterator* it)
3918  : it_(it), begin_was_called_(false) {
3919  it_->Init();
3920  }
3921  struct Iterator;
3922  Iterator begin() {
3923  if (DEBUG_MODE) {
3924  DCHECK(!begin_was_called_);
3925  begin_was_called_ = true;
3926  }
3927  return Iterator::Begin(it_);
3928  }
3929  Iterator end() { return Iterator::End(it_); }
3930 
3931  struct Iterator {
3932  // These are the only way to construct an Iterator.
3933  static Iterator Begin(IntVarIterator* it) {
3934  return Iterator(it, /*is_end=*/false);
3935  }
3936  static Iterator End(IntVarIterator* it) {
3937  return Iterator(it, /*is_end=*/true);
3938  }
3939 
3940  int64 operator*() const {
3941  DCHECK(it_->Ok());
3942  return it_->Value();
3943  }
3944  Iterator& operator++() {
3945  DCHECK(it_->Ok());
3946  it_->Next();
3947  return *this;
3948  }
3949  bool operator!=(const Iterator& other) const {
3950  DCHECK(other.it_ == it_);
3951  DCHECK(other.is_end_);
3952  return it_->Ok();
3953  }
3954 
3955  private:
3956  Iterator(IntVarIterator* it, bool is_end) : it_(it), is_end_(is_end) {}
3957 
3958  IntVarIterator* const it_;
3959  const bool is_end_;
3960  };
3961 
3962  private:
3963  IntVarIterator* const it_;
3964  bool begin_was_called_;
3965 };
3966 #endif // SWIG

4204  int64 step_;
4205  int64 best_;
4206  bool maximize_;
4207  bool found_initial_solution_;
4208 
4209  private:
4210  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(OptimizeVar);
4211 };

4213 // ---------- Search Limits ----------
4214 
4215 // Base class of all search limits.
4216 class SearchLimit : public SearchMonitor {
4217  public:
4218  explicit SearchLimit(Solver* const s) : SearchMonitor(s), crossed_(false) {}
4219  ~SearchLimit() override;
4220 
4221  // Returns true if the limit has been crossed.
4222  bool crossed() const { return crossed_; }
4223 
4224  // This method is called to check the status of the limit. A return
4225  // value of true indicates that we have indeed crossed the limit. In
4226  // that case, this method will not be called again and the remaining
4227  // search will be discarded.
4228  virtual bool Check() = 0;
4229 
4230  // This method is called when the search limit is initialized.
4231  virtual void Init() = 0;
4232 
4233  // Copy a limit. Warning: leads to a direct (no check) downcasting of 'limit'
4234  // so one needs to be sure both SearchLimits are of the same type.
4235  virtual void Copy(const SearchLimit* const limit) = 0;
4236 
4237  // Allocates a clone of the limit.
4238  virtual SearchLimit* MakeClone() const = 0;
4239 
4240  // Internal methods.
4241  void EnterSearch() override;
4242  void BeginNextDecision(DecisionBuilder* const b) override;
4243  void PeriodicCheck() override;
4244  void RefuteDecision(Decision* const d) override;
4245  std::string DebugString() const override {
4246  return absl::StrFormat("SearchLimit(crossed = %i)", crossed_);
4247  }
4248 
4249  private:
4250  void TopPeriodicCheck();
4251 
4252  bool crossed_;
4253  DISALLOW_COPY_AND_ASSIGN(SearchLimit);
4254 };

4256 // ----- Regular Limit -----

4258 // Usual limit based on wall_time, number of explored branches and
4259 // number of failures in the search tree
4260 class RegularLimit : public SearchLimit {
4261  public:
4262  RegularLimit(Solver* const s, int64 time, int64 branches, int64 failures,
4263  int64 solutions, bool smart_time_check, bool cumulative);
4264  ~RegularLimit() override;
4265  void Copy(const SearchLimit* const limit) override;
4266  SearchLimit* MakeClone() const override;
4267  RegularLimit* MakeIdenticalClone() const;
4268  bool Check() override;
4269  void Init() override;
4270  void ExitSearch() override;
4271  void UpdateLimits(int64 time, int64 branches, int64 failures,
4272  int64 solutions);
4273  absl::Duration duration_limit() const { return duration_limit_; }
4274  int64 wall_time() const {
4275  return duration_limit_ == absl::InfiniteDuration()
4276  ? kint64max
4277  : absl::ToInt64Milliseconds(duration_limit());
4278  }
4279  int64 branches() const { return branches_; }
4280  int64 failures() const { return failures_; }
4281  int64 solutions() const { return solutions_; }
4282  bool IsUncheckedSolutionLimitReached() override;
4283  int ProgressPercent() override;
4284  std::string DebugString() const override;
4285 
4286  absl::Time AbsoluteSolverDeadline() const {
4287  return solver_time_at_limit_start_ + duration_limit_;
4288  }
4289 
4290  void Accept(ModelVisitor* const visitor) const override;
4291 
4292  private:
4293  bool CheckTime();
4294  absl::Duration TimeElapsed();
4295  static int64 GetPercent(int64 value, int64 offset, int64 total) {
4296  return (total > 0 && total < kint64max) ? 100 * (value - offset) / total
4297  : -1;
4298  }
4299 
4300  absl::Duration duration_limit_;
4301  absl::Time solver_time_at_limit_start_;
4302  absl::Duration last_time_elapsed_;
4303  int64 check_count_;
4304  int64 next_check_;
4305  bool smart_time_check_;
4306  int64 branches_;
4307  int64 branches_offset_;
4308  int64 failures_;
4309  int64 failures_offset_;
4310  int64 solutions_;
4311  int64 solutions_offset_;
4312  // If cumulative if false, then the limit applies to each search
4313  // independently. If it's true, the limit applies globally to all search for
4314  // which this monitor is used.
4315  // When cumulative is true, the offset fields have two different meanings
4316  // depending on context:
4317  // - within a search, it's an offset to be subtracted from the current value
4318  // - outside of search, it's the amount consumed in previous searches
4319  bool cumulative_;
4320 };

4322 // ---------- Interval Var ----------
4323 
4324 // Interval variables are often used in scheduling. The main characteristics
4325 // of an IntervalVar are the start position, duration, and end
4326 // date. All these characteristics can be queried and set, and demons can
4327 // be posted on their modifications.
4328 //
4329 // An important aspect is optionality: an IntervalVar can be performed or not.
4330 // If unperformed, then it simply does not exist, and its characteristics
4331 // cannot be accessed any more. An interval var is automatically marked
4332 // as unperformed when it is not consistent anymore (start greater
4333 // than end, duration < 0...)
4334 class IntervalVar : public PropagationBaseObject {
4335  public:
4336  // The smallest acceptable value to be returned by StartMin()
4337  static const int64 kMinValidValue;
4338  // The largest acceptable value to be returned by EndMax()
4339  static const int64 kMaxValidValue;
4340  IntervalVar(Solver* const solver, const std::string& name)
4341  : PropagationBaseObject(solver) {
4342  set_name(name);
4343  }
4344  ~IntervalVar() override {}
4345 
4346  // These methods query, set, and watch the start position of the
4347  // interval var.
4348  virtual int64 StartMin() const = 0;
4349  virtual int64 StartMax() const = 0;
4350  virtual void SetStartMin(int64 m) = 0;
4351  virtual void SetStartMax(int64 m) = 0;
4352  virtual void SetStartRange(int64 mi, int64 ma) = 0;
4353  virtual int64 OldStartMin() const = 0;
4354  virtual int64 OldStartMax() const = 0;
4355  virtual void WhenStartRange(Demon* const d) = 0;
4356  void WhenStartRange(Solver::Closure closure) {
4357  WhenStartRange(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4358  }
4359 #if !defined(SWIG)
4360  void WhenStartRange(Solver::Action action) {
4361  WhenStartRange(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4362  }
4363 #endif // SWIG
4364  virtual void WhenStartBound(Demon* const d) = 0;
4365  void WhenStartBound(Solver::Closure closure) {
4366  WhenStartBound(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4367  }
4368 #if !defined(SWIG)
4369  void WhenStartBound(Solver::Action action) {
4370  WhenStartBound(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4371  }
4372 #endif // SWIG
4373 
4374  // These methods query, set, and watch the duration of the interval var.
4375  virtual int64 DurationMin() const = 0;
4376  virtual int64 DurationMax() const = 0;
4377  virtual void SetDurationMin(int64 m) = 0;
4378  virtual void SetDurationMax(int64 m) = 0;
4379  virtual void SetDurationRange(int64 mi, int64 ma) = 0;
4380  virtual int64 OldDurationMin() const = 0;
4381  virtual int64 OldDurationMax() const = 0;
4382  virtual void WhenDurationRange(Demon* const d) = 0;
4383  void WhenDurationRange(Solver::Closure closure) {
4384  WhenDurationRange(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4385  }
4386 #if !defined(SWIG)
4387  void WhenDurationRange(Solver::Action action) {
4388  WhenDurationRange(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4389  }
4390 #endif // SWIG
4391  virtual void WhenDurationBound(Demon* const d) = 0;
4392  void WhenDurationBound(Solver::Closure closure) {
4393  WhenDurationBound(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4394  }
4395 #if !defined(SWIG)
4396  void WhenDurationBound(Solver::Action action) {
4397  WhenDurationBound(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4398  }
4399 #endif // SWIG
4400 
4401  // These methods query, set, and watch the end position of the interval var.
4402  virtual int64 EndMin() const = 0;
4403  virtual int64 EndMax() const = 0;
4404  virtual void SetEndMin(int64 m) = 0;
4405  virtual void SetEndMax(int64 m) = 0;
4406  virtual void SetEndRange(int64 mi, int64 ma) = 0;
4407  virtual int64 OldEndMin() const = 0;
4408  virtual int64 OldEndMax() const = 0;
4409  virtual void WhenEndRange(Demon* const d) = 0;
4410  void WhenEndRange(Solver::Closure closure) {
4411  WhenEndRange(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4412  }
4413 #if !defined(SWIG)
4414  void WhenEndRange(Solver::Action action) {
4415  WhenEndRange(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4416  }
4417 #endif // SWIG
4418  virtual void WhenEndBound(Demon* const d) = 0;
4419  void WhenEndBound(Solver::Closure closure) {
4420  WhenEndBound(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4421  }
4422 #if !defined(SWIG)
4423  void WhenEndBound(Solver::Action action) {
4424  WhenEndBound(solver()->MakeActionDemon(std::move(action)));
4425  }
4426 #endif // SWIG
4427 
4428  // These methods query, set, and watch the performed status of the
4429  // interval var.
4430  virtual bool MustBePerformed() const = 0;
4431  virtual bool MayBePerformed() const = 0;
4432  bool CannotBePerformed() const { return !MayBePerformed(); }
4433  bool IsPerformedBound() const {
4434  return MustBePerformed() || !MayBePerformed();
4435  }
4436  virtual void SetPerformed(bool val) = 0;

4438  virtual void WhenPerformedBound(Demon* const d) = 0;
4439  void WhenPerformedBound(Solver::Closure closure) {
4440  WhenPerformedBound(solver()->MakeClosureDemon(std::move(closure)));
4441  }
4442 #if !defined(SWIG)
